<subSubSection id="C32DBFF4D906FFFEFF4A52B36427116B" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="585" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B88EC7FD906FFF9FF4A52B36699178E" blockId="3.[151,1437,1785,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FF4A52B36419171D" bold="true" box="[199,322,1785,1811]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FD8852B36726171D" authorityName="Silvestri" authorityYear="1901" box="[517,637,1785,1811]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FD8852B36726171D" box="[517,637,1785,1811]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Amitermes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the soldier of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FCAC52B3669E171D" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1920" box="[801,965,1785,1811]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FCAC52B3669E171D" box="[801,965,1785,1811]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">A. californicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most closely resembles that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FA9352B360C7171D" baseAuthorityName="Desneux" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[1310,1436,1785,1811]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FA9352B360C7171D" box="[1310,1436,1785,1811]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">A. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FF3D5357647D1739" authorityName="Scheffrahn, Su, Mangold" authorityYear="1989" box="[176,294,1821,1847]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridensis">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FF3D5357647D1739" box="[176,294,1821,1847]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">floridensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The mandible bases, blades, and marginal teeth of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FCFC5357614D1739" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1920" box="[881,1046,1821,1847]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FCFC5357614D1739" box="[881,1046,1821,1847]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">A. californicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are larger and stouter in all respect than those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FEBF530B64E91755" baseAuthorityName="Desneux" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[306,434,1857,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FEBF530B64E91755" box="[306,434,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">A. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FE59530B67111755" authorityName="Scheffrahn, Su, Mangold" authorityYear="1989" box="[468,586,1857,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridensis">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FE59530B67111755" box="[468,586,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">floridensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation id="130CF0FAD906FFF9FDEE530B67921752" box="[611,713,1857,1884]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 2" captionStart-1="FIGURE 3" captionStart-2="FIGURE 4" captionStart-3="FIGURE 5" captionStartId-0="2.[151,250,1993,2017]" captionStartId-1="3.[151,250,1679,1703]" captionStartId-2="4.[151,250,986,1010]" captionStartId-3="4.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox-0="[186,1389,383,1969]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1435,181,1655]" captionTargetBox-2="[177,1410,417,959]" captionTargetBox-3="[181,1406,1070,1952]" captionTargetId-0="figure-113@2.[186,1400,381,1969]" captionTargetId-1="figure-15@3.[151,1435,181,1655]" captionTargetId-2="figure-123@4.[177,1410,417,963]" captionTargetId-3="figure-152@4.[181,1406,1070,1952]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionTargetPageId-2="4" captionTargetPageId-3="4" captionText-0="FIGURE 2. Measurements (Table 1) used to compare soldiers of Amitermes californicus (top) and A. wheeleri (bottom)." captionText-1="FIGURE 3. Amitermes soldier head capsules, dorsal view: A, B. A. californicus from Twenty Nine Palms, California; C, D. A. wheeleri from Corpus Christi, Texas; E, F. A. wheeleri from St. Petersburg, Florida." captionText-2="FIGURE 4. Dorsal view of Amitermes soldier mandibles: A, A. californicus from Pala, California; B, A. wheeleri from Pedernales Falls, Texas." captionText-3="FIGURE 5. Worker enteric valve armature: A,. A. californicus from Madera Canyon, Arizona; B, A. wheeleri from Boerne, Texas." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480098" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480100" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480102" figureDoi-3="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480104" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6480098/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6480100/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/6480102/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/6480104/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Figs 2–5</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation id="C6B5D9C4D906FFF9FD5B530B66731755" box="[726,808,1857,1883]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,239,151,175]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="TABLE 1. Measurements (mm) of Amitermes soldiers." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF48BCF7D900FFFFFF1A54DD67BE10A1" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" tableUuid="DF48BCF7D900FFFFFF1A54DD67BE10A1">Table 1</tableCitation>
). The soldier of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FC64530B61D41755" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1920" box="[1001,1167,1857,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FC64530B61D41755" box="[1001,1167,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">A. californicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is somewhat larger and has a more quadrate head capsule than that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FD11532F66401771" baseAuthorityName="Desneux" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[668,795,1893,1919]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FD11532F66401771" box="[668,795,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">A. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD906FFF9FCB1532F66E91771" authorityName="Scheffrahn, Su, Mangold" authorityYear="1989" box="[828,946,1893,1919]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridensis">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FCB1532F66E91771" box="[828,946,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">floridensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B88EC7FD906FFFEFF4A53C361471113" blockId="3.[151,1437,1785,2028]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,150,393]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="585" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis id="B943306DD906FFF9FF4A53C3647217AD" bold="true" box="[199,297,1929,1955]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Worker.</emphasis>
The description by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA6918ED906FFF9FD9853C367E817AD" author="Light, S. F." box="[533,691,1929,1955]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" pagination="173 - 214" refId="ref3412" refString="Light, S. F. (1930 a) The California species of the genus Amitermes Silvestri (Isoptera). University of California Publications in Entomology, 5, 173 - 214." type="journal article" year="1930">Light (1930a)</bibRefCitation>
is adequate but lacking the following additional characters: The second proctodeal segment (P2) very narrow and tubular; seating consists of circular flare connecting to the third proctodeal segment. Enteric valve armature (
<figureCitation id="130CF0FAD906FFF9FD19539B67B617E2" box="[660,749,2001,2028]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[181,1406,1070,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-152@4.[181,1406,1070,1952]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Worker enteric valve armature: A,. A. californicus from Madera Canyon, Arizona; B, A. wheeleri from Boerne, Texas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480104" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480104/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
) with six cushions extending length of P2; posterior ends of cushion consisting of ovoid patches of pointy scales varying in number from about 25 to about eight. The cushion with the most posterior scales has a string of single scales extending to its anterior where scales divide into two or three strings. Other cushions lack a string, but their anterior terminations have scale strings or scale patches. The cushion with the least number of scales is always opposite that with the greatest.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B88EC7FD901FFFEFF4A556C6427116B" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,393]" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis id="B943306DD901FFFEFF4A556C6419114E" bold="true" box="[199,322,294,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The workers of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD901FFFEFE75556D67C6114F" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1920" box="[504,669,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="4" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis id="B943306DD901FFFEFE75556D67C6114F" box="[504,669,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">A. californicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3797FCD901FFFEFD5E556D6611114F" baseAuthorityName="Desneux" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[723,842,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Termitidae" genus="Amitermes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Blattodea" pageId="4" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="B943306DD901FFFEFD5E556D6611114F" box="[723,842,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">A wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can only be separated by the former’s larger size and longer EVA (
<figureCitation id="130CF0FAD901FFFEFEA455016435116B" box="[297,366,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[181,1406,1070,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-152@4.[181,1406,1070,1952]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Worker enteric valve armature: A,. A. californicus from Madera Canyon, Arizona; B, A. wheeleri from Boerne, Texas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480104" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480104/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="585">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
